[49m[39m    1,   1[0m:[39m[49m # Recipe 9.9: Surgical Video Analysis
[0m[49m[39m    2,   2[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    3,   3[0m:[39m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Research/Pilot · **Estimated Cost:** ~$2.50–$8.00 per procedure (processing only)
[0m[49m[39m    4,   4[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    5,   5[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m    6,   6[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    7,   7[0m:[39m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[39m    8,   8[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    9,   9[0m:[39m[49m A surgeon performs a laparoscopic cholecystectomy. The camera records everything: 45 minutes of video showing instrument movements, tissue manipulation, anatomical landmarks appearing and disappearing behind smoke and blood. When the case is over, that video sits on a local drive in the OR. Nobody watches it unless something went wrong.
[0m[49m[39m   10,  10[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   11,  11[0m:[39m[49m This is a massive waste of information.
[0m[49m[39m   12,  12[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   13,  13[0m:[39m[49m Surgical video contains a dense record of what happened, when, and how. It captures technique, decision-making, complications, near-misses, and workflow efficiency in a way that no operative note ever could. An operative note says "the cystic duct was identified and clipped." The video shows the 90 seconds of careful dissection that preceded that clip, the moment of hesitation when the anatomy was unclear, and the subtle instrument repositioning that avoided a bile duct injury.
[0m[49m[39m   14,  14[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   15,  15[0m:[39m[49m The problem is scale. A busy hospital generates thousands of hours of surgical video per year. No human can watch all of it. Quality improvement programs sample a handful of cases. Training programs review selected clips. Morbidity and mortality conferences look at cases after adverse events. The vast majority of surgical video is never analyzed.
[0m[49m[39m   16,  16[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   17,  17[0m:[39m[49m What if you could automatically understand what's happening in every frame? Identify which phase of the procedure is underway. Detect which instruments are in the field. Recognize critical anatomical structures. Flag moments where complications are developing. Build a searchable, structured index of every surgical case.
[0m[49m[39m   18,  18[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   19,  19[0m:[39m[49m That's surgical video analysis. It's one of the most computationally demanding problems in healthcare AI, and it's still largely in the research phase for clinical deployment. But the technology has matured enough that pilot implementations are realistic, and the potential impact on surgical quality, training, and safety is enormous.
[0m[49m[39m   20,  20[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   21,  21[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   22,  22[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   23,  23[0m:[39m[49m ## The Technology: How Computers Understand Surgery
[0m[49m[39m   24,  24[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   25,  25[0m:[39m[49m ### Video Understanding: Beyond Single Frames
[0m[49m[39m   26,  26[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   27,  27[0m:[39m[49m Understanding surgical video is fundamentally different from analyzing a single medical image (like an X-ray or pathology slide). A single frame from a surgical video is often uninformative or ambiguous. You might see a metal instrument tip, some pink tissue, and a lot of smoke. Without temporal context (what came before, what comes after), even an expert surgeon might struggle to identify exactly what's happening.
[0m[49m[39m   28,  28[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   29,  29[0m:[39m[49m Video understanding requires reasoning across time. The field has evolved through several generations:
[0m[49m[39m   30,  30[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   31,  31[0m:[39m[49m **Frame-level classification** was the earliest approach. Process each frame independently through an image classifier. This works for simple tasks (is an instrument visible? yes/no) but fails for anything requiring temporal context. You can't identify a surgical phase from a single frame because the same visual appearance might occur in multiple phases.
[0m[49m[39m   32,  32[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   33,  33[0m:[39m[49m **Temporal convolutional networks (TCNs)** process sequences of frame-level features. They apply 1D convolutions across time, capturing local temporal patterns. A TCN can learn that "grasper visible + cautery active + tissue retraction" sustained over 30 seconds likely indicates a dissection phase. TCNs are efficient and work well for phase recognition when the phases are relatively long and distinct.
[0m[49m[39m   34,  34[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   35,  35[0m:[39m[49m **Recurrent architectures (LSTMs, GRUs)** maintain a hidden state that accumulates information over time. They're good at capturing long-range dependencies ("we're still in the same phase we entered 5 minutes ago") but struggle with very long sequences and can be expensive to train.
[0m[49m[39m   36,  36[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   37,  37[0m:[39m[49m **Transformer-based models** have become the state of the art for surgical video. Self-attention mechanisms can relate any frame to any other frame in the sequence, regardless of temporal distance. A transformer can learn that the current frame is related to something that happened 10 minutes ago (like a specific anatomical exposure that's now being referenced). The downside: transformers are computationally hungry, especially on long video sequences. Most practical implementations use a hierarchical approach: extract features at the frame level with a CNN, then process the feature sequence with a transformer.
[0m[49m[39m   38,  38[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   39,  39[0m:[39m[49m **Multi-task architectures** jointly predict multiple things: phase, instrument presence, anatomical structures, and actions. These tend to outperform single-task models because the tasks are correlated (certain instruments appear in certain phases, certain anatomy is visible during certain actions). Sharing representations across tasks provides implicit regularization.
[0m[49m[39m   40,  40[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   41,  41[0m:[39m[49m ### The Core Tasks
[0m[49m[39m   42,  42[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   43,  43[0m:[39m[49m Surgical video analysis encompasses several distinct recognition problems:
[0m[49m[39m   44,  44[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   45,  45[0m:[39m[49m **Phase recognition** identifies which stage of the procedure is currently underway. A laparoscopic cholecystectomy might have phases like: port placement, initial dissection, Calot's triangle dissection, clipping and cutting, gallbladder separation, extraction, and inspection. Phase recognition is the most mature task, with research models achieving 85-92% accuracy on benchmark datasets.
[0m[49m[39m   46,  46[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   47,  47[0m:[39m[49m **Instrument detection and tracking** identifies which surgical tools are visible in each frame and where they are. This is typically framed as object detection (bounding boxes around instruments) or instance segmentation (pixel-level masks). Challenges include occlusion (instruments behind tissue or smoke), motion blur, and the visual similarity between different instrument types.
[0m[49m[39m   48,  48[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   49,  49[0m:[39m[49m **Anatomy recognition** identifies critical anatomical structures. In cholecystectomy, this means the cystic duct, cystic artery, common bile duct, and hepatocystic triangle. This is arguably the highest-value task for safety: the most dangerous complication in cholecystectomy (bile duct injury) occurs when the surgeon misidentifies anatomy. A system that can reliably highlight the common bile duct could serve as a real-time safety check.
[0m[49m[39m   50,  50[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   51,  51[0m:[39m[49m **Action recognition** identifies what the surgeon is doing at a fine-grained level: grasping, cutting, clipping, cauterizing, retracting, irrigating. This combines instrument detection with motion analysis. It's useful for workflow analysis and training assessment.
[0m[49m[39m   52,  52[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   53,  53[0m:[39m[49m **Event detection** identifies specific moments of clinical significance: bleeding events, instrument-tissue contact, clip placement, specimen extraction. These are the moments you'd want to index for later retrieval.
[0m[49m[39m   54,  54[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   55,  55[0m:[39m[49m ### What Makes This Genuinely Hard
[0m[49m[39m   56,  56[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   57,  57[0m:[39m[49m Surgical video analysis is one of the most challenging computer vision problems in healthcare. Here's why:
[0m[49m[39m   58,  58[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   59,  59[0m:[39m[49m **Visual complexity.** The surgical field is visually chaotic. Tissue colors are similar across structures. Smoke from cautery obscures the view. Blood pools and flows. Lighting changes as the camera moves. Specular reflections from wet tissue create bright spots that confuse detectors. The visual signal-to-noise ratio is far worse than, say, a chest X-ray.
[0m[49m[39m   60,  60[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   61,  61[0m:[39m[49m **Temporal variability.** No two surgeries are identical. The same procedure performed by different surgeons, or by the same surgeon on different patients, will have different durations, different orderings of sub-steps, and different visual appearances. A phase recognition model trained on textbook-perfect cases will struggle with cases that deviate from the norm (which are exactly the cases you most want to analyze).
[0m[49m[39m   62,  62[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   63,  63[0m:[39m[49m **Annotation cost.** Training these models requires frame-level or segment-level annotations from expert surgeons. A single 45-minute video at 1 fps generates 2,700 frames that need labeling. At the phase level, this is manageable (annotate phase transitions). At the instrument or anatomy level, it requires bounding boxes or segmentation masks on individual frames. This is expensive, slow, and requires domain expertise that's in short supply.
[0m[49m[39m   64,  64[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   65,  65[0m:[39m[49m **Real-time constraints.** If you want to provide intraoperative feedback (not just post-hoc analysis), you need inference latency under 100-200 milliseconds per frame. That's achievable for simple classification but challenging for multi-task models processing high-resolution video.
[0m[49m[39m   66,  66[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   67,  67[0m:[39m[49m **Generalization across procedures.** A model trained on cholecystectomy doesn't transfer to appendectomy. The phases are different, the instruments are different, the anatomy is different. Building a general surgical video understanding system requires training data across many procedure types, which multiplies the annotation cost.
[0m[49m[39m   68,  68[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   69,  69[0m:[39m[49m **Data volume.** A single procedure at 30 fps and 1080p resolution generates roughly 50-100 GB of raw video. Even at reduced frame rates (1-5 fps for analysis), you're dealing with substantial storage and compute requirements. A hospital performing 20 surgeries per day generates terabytes of video per month.
[0m[49m[39m   70,  70[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   71,  71[0m:[39m[49m ### Where the Field Is Today
[0m[49m[39m   72,  72[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   73,  73[0m:[39m[49m The honest assessment: surgical video analysis is at the boundary between research and early clinical deployment.
[0m[49m[39m   74,  74[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   75,  75[0m:[39m[49m **Phase recognition** is the most mature. Several commercial products exist for specific procedures (primarily cholecystectomy and other laparoscopic procedures). Research accuracy on benchmark datasets (Cholec80, m2cai16) is in the 85-92% range. Clinical deployment is happening at a handful of academic centers.
[0m[49m[39m   76,  76[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   77,  77[0m:[39m[49m **Instrument detection** is commercially available in some surgical platforms. The da Vinci robotic system, for example, has built-in instrument tracking. For standard laparoscopic video, research models achieve reasonable detection accuracy but struggle with occlusion and unusual instrument configurations.
[0m[49m[39m   78,  78[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   79,  79[0m:[39m[49m **Anatomy recognition** is still primarily research-stage. The CholecSeg8k and other datasets have enabled progress, but clinical deployment requires higher accuracy than current models achieve, given the safety implications of misidentifying anatomy.
[0m[49m[39m   80,  80[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   81,  81[0m:[39m[49m **Real-time intraoperative feedback** is the holy grail and is not yet standard of care anywhere. A few research systems have demonstrated feasibility, but regulatory clearance, liability concerns, and workflow integration challenges remain significant barriers.
[0m[49m[39m   82,  82[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   83,  83[0m:[39m[49m For this recipe, we'll focus on a post-hoc analysis pipeline: processing recorded surgical video after the procedure for quality improvement, training, and research purposes. This sidesteps the real-time latency requirements and regulatory complexity of intraoperative systems while still delivering substantial value.
[0m[49m[39m   84,  84[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   85,  85[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   86,  86[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   87,  87[0m:[39m[49m ## General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[39m   88,  88[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   89,  89[0m:[39m[49m The pipeline for surgical video analysis follows this conceptual flow:
[0m[49m[39m   90,  90[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   91,  91[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   92,  92[0m:[39m[49m [Ingest Video] → [Preprocess / Sample Frames] → [Feature Extraction] → [Temporal Modeling] → [Multi-Task Prediction] → [Post-Processing] → [Structured Index] → [Query / Visualization]
[0m[49m[39m   93,  93[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   94,  94[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   95,  95[0m:[39m[49m **Ingest Video.** Surgical video arrives from the OR recording system. This might be a direct feed from the laparoscopic camera, a recording from the surgical robot, or a capture from an overhead camera. The video needs to land in durable storage with metadata: procedure type, surgeon, date, patient identifier (de-identified for research use cases).
[0m[49m[39m   96,  96[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   97,  97[0m:[39m[49m **Preprocess / Sample Frames.** Raw surgical video at 30 fps is far more data than you need for most analysis tasks. Phase transitions happen over seconds, not milliseconds. Sampling at 1-5 fps is standard for phase recognition. For instrument detection, you might want higher rates (5-10 fps) to capture fast movements. Preprocessing also includes resizing, normalization, and optionally removing non-informative frames (black frames from camera disconnection, frames with no visible tissue).
[0m[49m[39m   98,  98[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   99,  99[0m:[39m[49m **Feature Extraction.** Each sampled frame passes through a convolutional neural network (typically a ResNet-50 or similar backbone pretrained on ImageNet, then fine-tuned on surgical data) to produce a compact feature vector. This reduces each frame from millions of pixels to a few thousand numbers that encode the visual content. This step is the most computationally expensive per-frame operation.
[0m[49m[39m  100, 100[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  101, 101[0m:[39m[49m **Temporal Modeling.** The sequence of frame features passes through a temporal model (TCN, transformer, or hybrid) that reasons across time. This is where the system learns that "frame 1000 looks like dissection because frames 950-999 showed progressive tissue separation." The temporal model outputs per-frame predictions for each task.
[0m[49m[39m  102, 102[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  103, 103[0m:[39m[49m **Multi-Task Prediction.** The temporal model produces predictions for multiple tasks simultaneously: current phase, instruments present, visible anatomy, ongoing action. Joint prediction improves accuracy because the tasks constrain each other (you don't see a clip applier during the initial dissection phase).
[0m[49m[39m  104, 104[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  105, 105[0m:[39m[49m **Post-Processing.** Raw per-frame predictions are noisy. A phase might flicker between "dissection" and "clipping" for a few frames at the boundary. Post-processing applies temporal smoothing (you can't change phase for just one frame), minimum duration constraints (a phase must last at least N seconds), and transition logic (certain phase sequences are impossible).
[0m[49m[39m  106, 106[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  107, 107[0m:[39m[49m **Structured Index.** The final output is a structured record of the procedure: a timeline of phases with start/end timestamps, instrument usage logs, anatomy visibility windows, and flagged events. This lives in a queryable database.
[0m[49m[39m  108, 108[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  109, 109[0m:[39m[49m **Query / Visualization.** Downstream consumers access the structured index through APIs or visualization tools. A surgeon reviewing their cases can jump to specific phases. A quality committee can search for all cases where a specific complication indicator was flagged. A training program can compile clips showing exemplary technique at a specific step.
[0m[49m[39m  110, 110[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  111, 111[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  112, 112[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  113, 113[0m:[39m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[39m  114, 114[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  115, 115[0m:[39m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[39m  116, 116[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  117, 117[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon S3 for video storage.** Surgical video files are large (50-100 GB per procedure at full resolution) and write-once. S3 provides durable, encrypted storage with lifecycle policies to manage cost. Use S3 Intelligent-Tiering or transition to S3 Glacier for videos older than 90 days that aren't actively being analyzed. S3's multipart upload handles the large file sizes gracefully.
[0m[49m[39m  118, 118[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 119     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **AWS Elemental MediaConvert for video preprocessing.** Before ML analysis, you need to transcode surgical video into a consistent format, extract frames at your target sample rate, and optionally generate lower-resolution proxy copies for faster processing. MediaConvert handles format normalization and frame extraction as a managed service, avoiding the need to run FFmpeg on EC2 instances.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Elemental MediaConvert for video preprocessing.** Before ML analysis, you need to transcode surgical video into a consistent format, extract frames at your target sample rate, and optionally generate lower-resolution proxy copies for faster processing. MediaConvert handles format normalization and frame extraction as a managed service, avoiding the need to run FFmpeg on EC2 instances. MediaConvert accesses S3 via AWS-internal endpoints over TLS; data does not traverse the public internet. For organizations requiring all PHI processing within a VPC boundary, an alternative is running FFmpeg on a VPC-hosted EC2 instance or ECS task, at the cost of managing the compute infrastructure yourself.
[0m[49m[39m  120, 120[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  121, 121[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S1 (CRITICAL). Add PHI de-identification guidance for surgical video preprocessing: strip audio tracks (not needed for visual analysis but contain dense PHI), address pre-incision footage containing patient faces, sanitize video file metadata/headers, note OR monitor overlay detection for patient demographics displayed in-frame. -->
[0m[49m[39m  122, 122[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  123, 123[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for model training and batch inference.** Surgical video models require GPU compute for both training and inference. SageMaker provides managed training jobs with spot instance support (critical for the multi-day training runs these models require) and batch transform for processing video backlogs. For the feature extraction backbone, SageMaker's built-in support for PyTorch and distributed training across multiple GPUs is essential.
[0m[49m[39m  124, 124[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  125, 125[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Step Functions for pipeline orchestration.** The video analysis pipeline has multiple stages with dependencies, error handling requirements, and variable execution times. A single procedure might take 15-60 minutes to process depending on length. Step Functions manages the state machine: trigger on video upload, run preprocessing, launch inference, handle failures with retries, and write results.
[0m[49m[39m  126, 126[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  127, 127[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S5 (HIGH). Address SageMaker Batch Transform cold start (5-15 min provisioning overhead). Recommend batching strategies for medium volume (5-20 procedures/day) and real-time endpoints for high volume (>20/day). Adjust cost estimate to account for amortized cold start. -->
[0m[49m[39m  128, 128[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  129, 129[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for the structured index.** Phase timelines, instrument logs, and event flags are time-series data with procedure-level access patterns. DynamoDB's flexible schema handles the varying output structures across procedure types, and its query performance supports the interactive visualization use case.
[0m[49m[39m  130, 130[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  131, 131[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon OpenSearch Service for full-text and temporal search.** When a quality committee wants to find "all cholecystectomies where the critical view of safety was not clearly achieved" or "cases with bleeding events during Calot's triangle dissection," you need a search engine that can handle structured queries across the procedure index. OpenSearch supports both keyword search on annotations and range queries on timestamps.
[0m[49m[39m  132, 132[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  133, 133[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon CloudWatch for monitoring.** Processing pipelines for surgical video are long-running and resource-intensive. CloudWatch metrics track processing latency, GPU utilization, inference failures, and queue depth. Alarms catch stuck pipelines before the backlog grows.
[0m[49m[39m  134, 134[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  135, 135[0m:[39m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[39m  136, 136[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  137, 137[0m:[39m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[39m  138, 138[0m:[39m[49m flowchart TD
[0m[49m[39m  139, 139[0m:[39m[49m     A[🎥 OR Recording System] -->|Upload| B[S3 Bucket\nsurgical-video-raw/]
[0m[49m[39m  140, 140[0m:[39m[49m     B -->|S3 Event| C[Step Functions\nvideo-analysis-pipeline]
[0m[49m[39m  141, 141[0m:[39m[49m     C -->|Transcode + Extract Frames| D[MediaConvert]
[0m[49m[39m  142, 142[0m:[39m[49m     D -->|Frames at 1-5 fps| E[S3 Bucket\nsurgical-frames/]
[0m[49m[39m  143, 143[0m:[39m[49m     E -->|Batch Transform| F[SageMaker\nFeature Extraction\n+ Temporal Model]
[0m[49m[39m  144, 144[0m:[39m[49m     F -->|Predictions| G[Lambda\nPost-Processing]
[0m[49m[39m  145, 145[0m:[39m[49m     G -->|Structured Results| H[DynamoDB\nprocedure-index]
[0m[49m[39m  146, 146[0m:[39m[49m     G -->|Searchable Index| I[OpenSearch\nprocedure-search]
[0m[49m[39m  147, 147[0m:[39m[49m     H --> J[API Gateway\nQuery API]
[0m[49m[39m  148, 148[0m:[39m[49m     I --> J
[0m[49m[39m  149, 149[0m:[39m[49m     J --> K[📊 Visualization Dashboard]
[0m[49m[39m  150, 150[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  151, 151[0m:[39m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  152, 152[0m:[39m[49m     style F fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  153, 153[0m:[39m[49m     style H fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  154, 154[0m:[39m[49m     style I fill:#9cf,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[39m  155, 155[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  156, 156[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  157, 157[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  158, 158[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  159, 159[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  160, 160[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  161, 161[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon S3, AWS Elemental MediaConvert, Amazon SageMaker, AWS Step Functions, Amazon DynamoDB, Amazon OpenSearch Service, AWS Lambda, Amazon API Gateway, Amazon CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[39m  162, 162[0m:[39m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `s3:ListBucket`, `mediaconvert:CreateJob`, `mediaconvert:GetJob`, `sagemaker:CreateTransformJob`, `sagemaker:DescribeTransformJob`, `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, `es:ESHttpPost`, `es:ESHttpGet`, `lambda:InvokeFunction`, `states:StartExecution`, `states:DescribeExecution`, `kms:Decrypt`, `kms:GenerateDataKey`, `logs:CreateLogGroup`, `logs:PutLogEvents` |
[0m[49m[39m  163, 163[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (surgical video is PHI; even de-identified video may contain identifiable features) |
[0m[49m[39m  164, 164[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS for all buckets; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; OpenSearch: encryption at rest and node-to-node encryption; all transit over TLS; SageMaker: volume encryption on training and inference instances |
[0m[49m[39m  165, 165[0m:[39m[49m | **VPC** | Production: SageMaker, OpenSearch, and Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, DynamoDB, CloudWatch Logs, and Step Functions. OpenSearch domain must be VPC-only (no public endpoint for PHI data). Post-processing Lambda must be in the same VPC as the OpenSearch domain with security groups allowing HTTPS (443) to the OpenSearch domain's security group. |
[0m[49m[39m  166, 166[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all S3, SageMaker, and DynamoDB API calls for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[39m  167, 167[0m:[39m[49m | **GPU Instances** | SageMaker training: ml.p3.2xlarge or ml.g5.2xlarge minimum. Batch inference: ml.g5.xlarge. Budget for multi-day training runs. |
[0m[49m[39m  168, 168[0m:[39m[49m | **Sample Data** | Public surgical video datasets: Cholec80 (80 cholecystectomy videos with phase annotations), m2cai16 (tool and phase annotations), CholecSeg8k (semantic segmentation). These are research datasets. Real patient video requires IRB approval and proper de-identification. |
[0m[49m[39m  169, 169[0m:[39m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Processing: ~$2.50-$8.00 per procedure (MediaConvert + SageMaker inference). Training: ~$500-$2,000 per model training run (multi-day GPU). Storage: ~$1-2/month per procedure (S3 Intelligent-Tiering). OpenSearch: ~$200-500/month for a small domain. |
[0m[49m[39m  170, 170[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  171, 171[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S3 (HIGH). Expand IAM permissions into role-based groupings (Step Functions execution role, Lambda execution role, SageMaker execution role) with resource ARN scoping guidance rather than a flat list. -->
[0m[49m[39m  172, 172[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  173, 173[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  174, 174[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  175, 175[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  176, 176[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  177, 177[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores raw surgical video and extracted frames; lifecycle policies manage cost |
[0m[49m[39m  178, 178[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Elemental MediaConvert** | Transcodes video to consistent format; extracts frames at target sample rate |
[0m[49m[39m  179, 179[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Trains video analysis models (GPU); runs batch inference on new procedures |
[0m[49m[39m  180, 180[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates the multi-stage pipeline with error handling and retries |
[0m[49m[39m  181, 181[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores structured procedure index (phases, instruments, events) |
[0m[49m[39m  182, 182[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon OpenSearch Service** | Enables search across procedure annotations and temporal queries |
[0m[49m[39m  183, 183[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Post-processing logic, API handlers, pipeline glue |
[0m[49m[39m  184, 184[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | REST API for querying procedure index and search |
[0m[49m[39m  185, 185[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitoring, metrics, and alarms for pipeline health |
[0m[49m[39m  186, 186[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all data stores |
[0m[49m[39m  187, 187[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  188, 188[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  189, 189[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  190, 190[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  191, 191[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  192, 192[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Video ingestion and metadata registration.** When a surgical video arrives from the OR recording system, the pipeline registers it with metadata (procedure type, date, surgeon identifier, duration) and triggers processing. The video lands in an encrypted S3 bucket, and an S3 event notification kicks off the Step Functions state machine. This separation between storage and processing is important: if the analysis pipeline is down or backed up, videos still land safely and get processed when capacity is available. Skip this step (process inline during upload) and you risk losing video data if the processing pipeline fails.
[0m[49m[39m  193, 193[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  194, 194[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  195, 195[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION ingest_video(video_file, metadata):
[0m[49m[39m  196, 196[0m:[39m[49m     // Generate a unique identifier for this procedure.
[0m[49m[39m  197, 197[0m:[39m[49m     // This ID links the raw video, extracted frames, and analysis results.
[0m[49m[39m  198, 198[0m:[39m[49m     procedure_id = generate unique ID (e.g., UUID)
[0m[49m[39m  199, 199[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  200, 200[0m:[39m[49m     // Upload the video to encrypted storage.
[0m[49m[39m  201, 201[0m:[39m[49m     // Surgical video files are large (50-100 GB), so use multipart upload.
[0m[49m[39m  202, 202[0m:[39m[49m     upload video_file to S3 bucket "surgical-video-raw/"
[0m[49m[39m  203, 203[0m:[39m[49m         with key: "{procedure_id}/raw_video.mp4"
[0m[49m[39m  204, 204[0m:[39m[49m         with encryption: SSE-KMS
[0m[49m[39m  205, 205[0m:[39m[49m         with metadata: procedure_type, surgeon_id, procedure_date
[0m[49m[39m  206, 206[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  207, 207[0m:[39m[49m     // Register the procedure in the tracking database.
[0m[49m[39m  208, 208[0m:[39m[49m     // Status starts as "ingested" and progresses through the pipeline.
[0m[49m[39m  209, 209[0m:[39m[49m     write to DynamoDB table "procedure-registry":
[0m[49m[39m  210, 210[0m:[39m[49m         procedure_id    = procedure_id
[0m[49m[39m  211, 211[0m:[39m[49m         status          = "ingested"
[0m[49m[39m  212, 212[0m:[39m[49m         procedure_type  = metadata.procedure_type
[0m[49m[39m  213, 213[0m:[39m[49m         surgeon_id      = metadata.surgeon_id
[0m[49m[39m  214, 214[0m:[39m[49m         procedure_date  = metadata.procedure_date
[0m[49m[39m  215, 215[0m:[39m[49m         video_duration  = metadata.duration_seconds
[0m[49m[39m  216, 216[0m:[39m[49m         ingested_at     = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  217, 217[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  218, 218[0m:[39m[49m     // Trigger the analysis pipeline.
[0m[49m[39m  219, 219[0m:[39m[49m     start Step Functions execution with input:
[0m[49m[39m  220, 220[0m:[39m[49m         procedure_id = procedure_id
[0m[49m[39m  221, 221[0m:[39m[49m         video_key    = "{procedure_id}/raw_video.mp4"
[0m[49m[39m  222, 222[0m:[39m[49m         procedure_type = metadata.procedure_type
[0m[49m[39m  223, 223[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  224, 224[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN procedure_id
[0m[49m[39m  225, 225[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  226, 226[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  227, 227[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review A5 (HIGH). Add failure handling guidance: Step Functions catch-all state writing to a DLQ (SQS), CloudWatch alarm on DLQ depth, and a scheduled Lambda scanning for procedures stuck in "ingested" or "processing" status beyond a threshold for automatic retry. -->
[0m[49m[39m  228, 228[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  229, 229[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Frame extraction and preprocessing.** Raw surgical video at 30 fps contains far more temporal redundancy than the analysis models need. Phase transitions happen over seconds, not frames. This step extracts frames at a configurable sample rate (typically 1 fps for phase recognition, up to 5 fps for instrument detection), resizes them to the model's expected input resolution, and filters out non-informative frames (black frames from camera disconnection, completely obscured frames from lens fogging). The output is a sequence of clean, consistently-sized frames ready for feature extraction. Skip this step and you'll burn 30x more GPU compute on redundant frames with no accuracy improvement.
[0m[49m[39m  230, 230[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  231, 231[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  232, 232[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_frames(procedure_id, video_key, sample_rate_fps):
[0m[49m[39m  233, 233[0m:[39m[49m     // Use a managed transcoding service to extract frames.
[0m[49m[39m  234, 234[0m:[39m[49m     // This avoids running FFmpeg on EC2 and handles format inconsistencies
[0m[49m[39m  235, 235[0m:[39m[49m     // across different OR recording systems.
[0m[49m[39m  236, 236[0m:[39m[49m     create MediaConvert job:
[0m[49m[39m  237, 237[0m:[39m[49m         input:  S3 object at video_key
[0m[49m[39m  238, 238[0m:[39m[49m         output: S3 bucket "surgical-frames/{procedure_id}/"
[0m[49m[39m  239, 239[0m:[39m[49m         settings:
[0m[49m[39m  240, 240[0m:[39m[49m             frame_rate: sample_rate_fps        // typically 1-5 fps
[0m[49m[39m  241, 241[0m:[39m[49m             output_format: JPEG                // individual frame images
[0m[49m[39m  242, 242[0m:[39m[49m             resolution: 224x224 or 384x384     // match model input size
[0m[49m[39m  243, 243[0m:[39m[49m             // Some OR systems record in unusual formats or codecs.
[0m[49m[39m  244, 244[0m:[39m[49m             // MediaConvert normalizes these automatically.
[0m[49m[39m  245, 245[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  246, 246[0m:[39m[49m     // Wait for the transcoding job to complete.
[0m[49m[39m  247, 247[0m:[39m[49m     // A 45-minute video at 1 fps produces ~2,700 frames.
[0m[49m[39m  248, 248[0m:[39m[49m     wait for job completion (poll or use EventBridge)
[0m[49m[39m  249, 249[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  250, 250[0m:[39m[49m     // Filter out non-informative frames.
[0m[49m[39m  251, 251[0m:[39m[49m     // Black frames occur when the camera is disconnected or the light source is off.
[0m[49m[39m  252, 252[0m:[39m[49m     // Completely white/washed-out frames occur from lens fogging or direct light.
[0m[49m[39m  253, 253[0m:[39m[49m     frame_list = list all frames in "surgical-frames/{procedure_id}/"
[0m[49m[39m  254, 254[0m:[39m[49m     valid_frames = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  255, 255[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  256, 256[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each frame in frame_list:
[0m[49m[39m  257, 257[0m:[39m[49m         pixel_stats = compute mean and standard deviation of pixel values
[0m[49m[39m  258, 258[0m:[39m[49m         IF pixel_stats.mean < 10:
[0m[49m[39m  259, 259[0m:[39m[49m             SKIP  // black frame (camera off or disconnected)
[0m[49m[39m  260, 260[0m:[39m[49m         IF pixel_stats.std < 5:
[0m[49m[39m  261, 261[0m:[39m[49m             SKIP  // uniform frame (lens cap, complete fog, or saturation)
[0m[49m[39m  262, 262[0m:[39m[49m         append frame to valid_frames
[0m[49m[39m  263, 263[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  264, 264[0m:[39m[49m     // Write the valid frame manifest for downstream processing.
[0m[49m[39m  265, 265[0m:[39m[49m     write valid_frames list to S3: "surgical-frames/{procedure_id}/manifest.json"
[0m[49m[39m  266, 266[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  267, 267[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN count of valid_frames
[0m[49m[39m  268, 268[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  269, 269[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  270, 270[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Feature extraction.** Each valid frame passes through a convolutional neural network (the "backbone") that compresses the visual information into a compact feature vector. Think of this as translating each frame from "millions of pixel values" into "a few thousand numbers that capture what's visually important." The backbone is typically a ResNet-50 or similar architecture pretrained on ImageNet (general image recognition) and then fine-tuned on surgical video data. Fine-tuning is critical: a model trained only on natural images doesn't understand that "pink tissue with a metal instrument" is the normal state of affairs in surgery. This step is the most GPU-intensive per-frame operation, but it only needs to run once per frame. The extracted features are cached for use by multiple downstream models.
[0m[49m[39m  271, 271[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  272, 272[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  273, 273[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_features(procedure_id, frame_manifest):
[0m[49m[39m  274, 274[0m:[39m[49m     // Load the fine-tuned feature extraction model.
[0m[49m[39m  275, 275[0m:[39m[49m     // This is a CNN backbone (e.g., ResNet-50) trained on surgical video.
[0m[49m[39m  276, 276[0m:[39m[49m     // The final classification layer is removed; we want the feature vector,
[0m[49m[39m  277, 277[0m:[39m[49m     // not a class prediction.
[0m[49m[39m  278, 278[0m:[39m[49m     model = load pretrained surgical feature extractor
[0m[49m[39m  279, 279[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  280, 280[0m:[39m[49m     features = empty list (will hold one feature vector per frame)
[0m[49m[39m  281, 281[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  282, 282[0m:[39m[49m     // Process frames in batches for GPU efficiency.
[0m[49m[39m  283, 283[0m:[39m[49m     // Batch size depends on GPU memory; 32-64 frames per batch is typical.
[0m[49m[39m  284, 284[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each batch of frames from frame_manifest:
[0m[49m[39m  285, 285[0m:[39m[49m         // Load frame images and normalize pixel values.
[0m[49m[39m  286, 286[0m:[39m[49m         // Normalization uses the same mean/std as the training data.
[0m[49m[39m  287, 287[0m:[39m[49m         images = load and normalize batch of frame images from S3
[0m[49m[39m  288, 288[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  289, 289[0m:[39m[49m         // Forward pass through the CNN backbone.
[0m[49m[39m  290, 290[0m:[39m[49m         // Output shape: [batch_size, feature_dim] where feature_dim is typically 2048.
[0m[49m[39m  291, 291[0m:[39m[49m         batch_features = model.forward(images)  // GPU operation
[0m[49m[39m  292, 292[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  293, 293[0m:[39m[49m         append batch_features to features
[0m[49m[39m  294, 294[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  295, 295[0m:[39m[49m     // Save the feature sequence to S3 for temporal modeling.
[0m[49m[39m  296, 296[0m:[39m[49m     // This is much smaller than the raw frames: ~8 KB per frame vs. ~150 KB per frame.
[0m[49m[39m  297, 297[0m:[39m[49m     save features array to S3: "surgical-features/{procedure_id}/features.npy"
[0m[49m[39m  298, 298[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  299, 299[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN feature array shape (num_frames, feature_dim)
[0m[49m[39m  300, 300[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  301, 301[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  302, 302[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Temporal modeling and multi-task prediction.** This is where the system reasons across time. The sequence of frame features (from Step 3) passes through a temporal model that considers the full context of the procedure to make predictions at each time point. A transformer-based architecture attends to all frames simultaneously, learning patterns like "this visual pattern following that visual pattern usually means we're transitioning from dissection to clipping." The model outputs predictions for multiple tasks: surgical phase, instrument presence, and (if trained for it) anatomy visibility. Joint prediction helps because the tasks constrain each other. You wouldn't expect to see a clip applier during the initial port placement phase. Skip this step and use only frame-level predictions, and you'll get noisy, temporally inconsistent results that flicker between phases every few frames.
[0m[49m[39m  303, 303[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  304, 304[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  305, 305[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION temporal_prediction(procedure_id, features):
[0m[49m[39m  306, 306[0m:[39m[49m     // Load the temporal model (transformer or TCN).
[0m[49m[39m  307, 307[0m:[39m[49m     // This model was trained on annotated surgical video sequences.
[0m[49m[39m  308, 308[0m:[39m[49m     // It takes a sequence of frame features and outputs per-frame predictions.
[0m[49m[39m  309, 309[0m:[39m[49m     temporal_model = load trained temporal model for procedure_type
[0m[49m[39m  310, 310[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  311, 311[0m:[39m[49m     // Run inference on the full feature sequence.
[0m[49m[39m  312, 312[0m:[39m[49m     // Input shape: [1, num_frames, feature_dim]
[0m[49m[39m  313, 313[0m:[39m[49m     // Output: per-frame predictions for each task
[0m[49m[39m  314, 314[0m:[39m[49m     predictions = temporal_model.forward(features)
[0m[49m[39m  315, 315[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  316, 316[0m:[39m[49m     // predictions contains:
[0m[49m[39m  317, 317[0m:[39m[49m     //   phase_logits:      [num_frames, num_phases]       - probability of each phase per frame
[0m[49m[39m  318, 318[0m:[39m[49m     //   instrument_logits: [num_frames, num_instruments]  - probability of each instrument per frame
[0m[49m[39m  319, 319[0m:[39m[49m     //   event_logits:      [num_frames, num_event_types]  - probability of each event type per frame
[0m[49m[39m  320, 320[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  321, 321[0m:[39m[49m     // Convert logits to probabilities and class predictions.
[0m[49m[39m  322, 322[0m:[39m[49m     phase_predictions = argmax(softmax(predictions.phase_logits), axis=1)
[0m[49m[39m  323, 323[0m:[39m[49m     phase_confidences = max(softmax(predictions.phase_logits), axis=1)
[0m[49m[39m  324, 324[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  325, 325[0m:[39m[49m     instrument_predictions = sigmoid(predictions.instrument_logits) > 0.5  // multi-label
[0m[49m[39m  326, 326[0m:[39m[49m     instrument_confidences = sigmoid(predictions.instrument_logits)
[0m[49m[39m  327, 327[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  328, 328[0m:[39m[49m     event_predictions = sigmoid(predictions.event_logits) > 0.3  // lower threshold for events
[0m[49m[39m  329, 329[0m:[39m[49m     event_confidences = sigmoid(predictions.event_logits)
[0m[49m[39m  330, 330[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  331, 331[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  332, 332[0m:[39m[49m         phases: phase_predictions with confidences,
[0m[49m[39m  333, 333[0m:[39m[49m         instruments: instrument_predictions with confidences,
[0m[49m[39m  334, 334[0m:[39m[49m         events: event_predictions with confidences,
[0m[49m[39m  335, 335[0m:[39m[49m         frame_timestamps: computed from frame indices and sample_rate
[0m[49m[39m  336, 336[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  337, 337[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  338, 338[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  339, 339[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Temporal post-processing.** Raw per-frame predictions from the temporal model are still noisy at phase boundaries. A phase might flicker for a few frames, or a brief instrument occlusion might cause a false "instrument absent" prediction. Post-processing applies domain knowledge to clean up the predictions: minimum phase duration constraints (a surgical phase can't last 2 seconds), transition smoothing (median filtering over a window), and impossible transition elimination (you can't go from "extraction" back to "initial dissection"). This step dramatically improves the usability of the output. Without it, the phase timeline would have dozens of spurious micro-transitions that make no surgical sense.
[0m[49m[39m  340, 340[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  341, 341[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  342, 342[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION post_process(raw_predictions, sample_rate_fps):
[0m[49m[39m  343, 343[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Phase smoothing ---
[0m[49m[39m  344, 344[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply median filter to remove single-frame phase flickers.
[0m[49m[39m  345, 345[0m:[39m[49m     // Window size of 15 frames at 1 fps = 15 seconds of smoothing.
[0m[49m[39m  346, 346[0m:[39m[49m     smoothed_phases = median_filter(raw_predictions.phases, window=15)
[0m[49m[39m  347, 347[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  348, 348[0m:[39m[49m     // Enforce minimum phase duration.
[0m[49m[39m  349, 349[0m:[39m[49m     // No surgical phase lasts less than 30 seconds in practice.
[0m[49m[39m  350, 350[0m:[39m[49m     MIN_PHASE_DURATION = 30 * sample_rate_fps  // 30 seconds worth of frames
[0m[49m[39m  351, 351[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  352, 352[0m:[39m[49m     segments = identify contiguous segments of same phase in smoothed_phases
[0m[49m[39m  353, 353[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each segment in segments:
[0m[49m[39m  354, 354[0m:[39m[49m         IF segment.duration < MIN_PHASE_DURATION:
[0m[49m[39m  355, 355[0m:[39m[49m             // Merge this short segment into the surrounding phase.
[0m[49m[39m  356, 356[0m:[39m[49m             // Use the phase of the longer neighbor.
[0m[49m[39m  357, 357[0m:[39m[49m             merge segment into longer adjacent segment
[0m[49m[39m  358, 358[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  359, 359[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Instrument smoothing ---
[0m[49m[39m  360, 360[0m:[39m[49m     // Brief instrument disappearances (< 3 seconds) are likely occlusion, not removal.
[0m[49m[39m  361, 361[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each instrument_type:
[0m[49m[39m  362, 362[0m:[39m[49m         fill gaps shorter than 3 * sample_rate_fps frames
[0m[49m[39m  363, 363[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  364, 364[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Build phase timeline ---
[0m[49m[39m  365, 365[0m:[39m[49m     phase_timeline = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  366, 366[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each contiguous phase segment:
[0m[49m[39m  367, 367[0m:[39m[49m         append to phase_timeline: {
[0m[49m[39m  368, 368[0m:[39m[49m             phase_name:  segment.phase_label,
[0m[49m[39m  369, 369[0m:[39m[49m             start_time:  segment.start_frame / sample_rate_fps,  // seconds
[0m[49m[39m  370, 370[0m:[39m[49m             end_time:    segment.end_frame / sample_rate_fps,
[0m[49m[39m  371, 371[0m:[39m[49m             duration:    (segment.end_frame - segment.start_frame) / sample_rate_fps,
[0m[49m[39m  372, 372[0m:[39m[49m             confidence:  mean confidence of frames in segment
[0m[49m[39m  373, 373[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  374, 374[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  375, 375[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Build event list ---
[0m[49m[39m  376, 376[0m:[39m[49m     events = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  377, 377[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each detected event:
[0m[49m[39m  378, 378[0m:[39m[49m         append to events: {
[0m[49m[39m  379, 379[0m:[39m[49m             event_type:  event.label,
[0m[49m[39m  380, 380[0m:[39m[49m             timestamp:   event.frame / sample_rate_fps,
[0m[49m[39m  381, 381[0m:[39m[49m             confidence:  event.confidence,
[0m[49m[39m  382, 382[0m:[39m[49m             context:     surrounding phase at that timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  383, 383[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  384, 384[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  385, 385[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  386, 386[0m:[39m[49m         phase_timeline: phase_timeline,
[0m[49m[39m  387, 387[0m:[39m[49m         instrument_log: instrument presence intervals,
[0m[49m[39m  388, 388[0m:[39m[49m         events: events,
[0m[49m[39m  389, 389[0m:[39m[49m         total_duration: total frames / sample_rate_fps
[0m[49m[39m  390, 390[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  391, 391[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  392, 392[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  393, 393[0m:[39m[49m **Step 6: Store structured index and enable search.** The post-processed results become a structured, queryable record of the procedure. This step writes the phase timeline, instrument usage, and events to both a fast-lookup store (DynamoDB for procedure-level queries) and a search index (OpenSearch for cross-procedure queries). The dual-write pattern serves different access patterns: "show me the timeline for procedure X" hits DynamoDB; "find all procedures where bleeding occurred during Calot's triangle dissection" hits OpenSearch. Skip the search index and you lose the ability to do population-level quality analysis, which is half the value of automated video analysis.
[0m[49m[39m  394, 394[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  395, 395[0m:[39m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S2 (CRITICAL). Add access control model for surgeon-identifiable performance data: pseudonymize surgeon_id in the general search index with a separate restricted lookup table, add role-based access control for surgeon-identified queries, note peer review protection requirements (vary by state, require legal counsel review), and add CloudTrail-based audit logging for queries that resolve surgeon identity. -->
[0m[49m[39m  396, 396[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  397, 397[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  398, 398[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION store_results(procedure_id, analysis_results):
[0m[49m[39m  399, 399[0m:[39m[49m     // Write the full procedure analysis to DynamoDB.
[0m[49m[39m  400, 400[0m:[39m[49m     // This supports fast lookup by procedure_id.
[0m[49m[39m  401, 401[0m:[39m[49m     write to DynamoDB table "procedure-index":
[0m[49m[39m  402, 402[0m:[39m[49m         procedure_id    = procedure_id
[0m[49m[39m  403, 403[0m:[39m[49m         status          = "analyzed"
[0m[49m[39m  404, 404[0m:[39m[49m         analyzed_at     = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  405, 405[0m:[39m[49m         phase_timeline  = analysis_results.phase_timeline
[0m[49m[39m  406, 406[0m:[39m[49m         instrument_log  = analysis_results.instrument_log
[0m[49m[39m  407, 407[0m:[39m[49m         events          = analysis_results.events
[0m[49m[39m  408, 408[0m:[39m[49m         total_duration  = analysis_results.total_duration
[0m[49m[39m  409, 409[0m:[39m[49m         model_version   = current model version identifier
[0m[49m[39m  410, 410[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  411, 411[0m:[39m[49m     // Index in OpenSearch for cross-procedure search.
[0m[49m[39m  412, 412[0m:[39m[49m     // Flatten the timeline into searchable documents.
[0m[49m[39m  413, 413[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each phase in analysis_results.phase_timeline:
[0m[49m[39m  414, 414[0m:[39m[49m         index in OpenSearch "procedure-phases":
[0m[49m[39m  415, 415[0m:[39m[49m             procedure_id  = procedure_id
[0m[49m[39m  416, 416[0m:[39m[49m             phase_name    = phase.phase_name
[0m[49m[39m  417, 417[0m:[39m[49m             start_time    = phase.start_time
[0m[49m[39m  418, 418[0m:[39m[49m             end_time      = phase.end_time
[0m[49m[39m  419, 419[0m:[39m[49m             duration      = phase.duration
[0m[49m[39m  420, 420[0m:[39m[49m             confidence    = phase.confidence
[0m[49m[39m  421, 421[0m:[39m[49m             procedure_type = metadata.procedure_type
[0m[49m[39m  422, 422[0m:[39m[49m             surgeon_id    = metadata.surgeon_id
[0m[49m[39m  423, 423[0m:[39m[49m             procedure_date = metadata.procedure_date
[0m[49m[39m  424, 424[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  425, 425[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each event in analysis_results.events:
[0m[49m[39m  426, 426[0m:[39m[49m         index in OpenSearch "procedure-events":
[0m[49m[39m  427, 427[0m:[39m[49m             procedure_id  = procedure_id
[0m[49m[39m  428, 428[0m:[39m[49m             event_type    = event.event_type
[0m[49m[39m  429, 429[0m:[39m[49m             timestamp     = event.timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  430, 430[0m:[39m[49m             confidence    = event.confidence
[0m[49m[39m  431, 431[0m:[39m[49m             phase_context = event.context
[0m[49m[39m  432, 432[0m:[39m[49m             procedure_type = metadata.procedure_type
[0m[49m[39m  433, 433[0m:[39m[49m             surgeon_id    = metadata.surgeon_id
[0m[49m[39m  434, 434[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  435, 435[0m:[39m[49m     // Update the procedure registry status.
[0m[49m[39m  436, 436[0m:[39m[49m     update DynamoDB "procedure-registry" where procedure_id:
[0m[49m[39m  437, 437[0m:[39m[49m         status = "complete"
[0m[49m[39m  438, 438[0m:[39m[49m         completed_at = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  439, 439[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  440, 440[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN success
[0m[49m[39m  441, 441[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  442, 442[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  443, 443[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter09.09-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
